I'm noticing more and more the number of acts who don't seem to know
what a &quot;short song&quot; is.  When I'm running something to a timetable and
the act says &quot;how many more?&quot; with three minutes left before the end
of their alloted time, I usually say &quot;time for one but short&quot;.  I'm
amazed at how many times this can then be followed by a quick re-tune
of the guitar, the story behind the song, then a five verse ballad
clocking in at 4 minutes or more. Am I not being clear enough?  Next
time I get asked, should I say - &quot;you have precisely 3 minutes and ten
seconds to introduce, play and get off&quot;?

At an open mike session, people sign up for 15 minute spots - and yet
some clearly didn't understand that four four-minute songs with intros
and applause don't fit into 15 minutes, never mind the setting up time
(adjusting mikes, finding capos, tuning, etc.).

Fair dos to some.  Rory McLeod played our club recently and the
evening finished perilously close to our cut-off time - when someone
pointed out he hadn't played his trombone.  I told him he had 30
seconds to give us something on the trombone - and he did exactly that!
