Oh lord! Yes, at festivals you can get all sorts of mixed signals if you
don't understand the stage manager's particular brand of semaphore. The
very first time we played Sidmouth we did a Radway cinema concert with
Roger Watson MCing. he warned us that time was short and not to overrun
and that he'd give us a five minute warning from the wings by giving us
the splayed hand... but we knew what time we were due to come off
anyway, so we were getting ready for the last song and looked into the
wings for Roger and 'the hand'... Nothing. So we did another song - not
the finisher and looked again... Nothing. Did another song and looked
over... Nothing.

By now the set was starting to get a bit ragged because we were making
it up as we went along without being able to have a confab. At last
Roger was there with the 'five' sign. We sang Mary Ellen Carter and
buggered off stage as fast as was decent.

It turned out they'd lost the act that was to follow us. No one had told
him about the stage door and he was sitting in the front row waiting to
climb up the front stage steps while they were looking everywhere but
the front row for him.

Semaphore certainly didn't communicate what was going on.

Jacey
