At our local music festival, we usually arrange with the performers
beforehand that we will give them a five minute signal.  At the small
stage that I manage, it's quite easy to give a quiet word from the
wings.  Even better, the sound man I work with will usually give a quiet
word through the monitors.  It has been suggested that placing an
agreed- upon object (eg.coffee cup) where the performers can see it is
another option.  Again, this is all much easier at  small stage.
(How about this for large stages:  A morris dance team wends its way
along the front of the stage holding up banners which proclaim &quot;Five
Minutes!&quot;  No - too subtle)
As for the earlier discussion about giving performers at a folk club
a specific length of time for their set, we have found, at an small
annual event here, that that didn't work very well for all the
aforementioned reasons so we tell everyone that they get to do three
songs.  this seems to work pretty well, the only trouble being that
there is always someone to whom you wish you could give more time. (this
is a &quot;floor spot&quot; type of event.)    Stephen H

